<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#00ff00" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">theNorio</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Just wondering where you guys got your experience, mainly the guys who have made the emu and utils ect, like scruffy, onezero and the ethernalquest guys,<BR>did you take courses in school? if so dont bother answering, its too late for that,<BR>did you learn it from books? which books, or series of books whatever<BR>or did you learn it from free downloads on the internet (the one im trying right now) with the useless readmes and missing exe compilers, and notepads that ALWAYS saves as .txt,<BR>anyway, ignore all that shit, where'd you learn it from?</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">kaoruAngel</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">It's all _documentation_, good _ideas_, and _examples_.<P>For programming in general, don't ignore the learning material that comes with the commercial programming IDE of your choice. I started with "that book that came with Borland C++ Builder." If you choose to program in C++, better choices that more fully cover the language and it's standards (praise The Standard) would be The C++ Programming Language, by Bjarne Stroustrup (creator of C++) and a good book simply on object-oriented design, such as &lt;ok, I forgot the name of the one I picked up&gt; by Booch. MSDN is a great free resource even if you're not programming for Windows, I would say. If you can deal with the concise and technical language used within it, the Standard C++ Working Draft is available free online.<P>Ideas, ideas, ideas! The language is nothing without a pretty damn spiff idea. This is where a lot of the success comes from.<P>Use the resources available to you. The internet brings access to help and examples illustrating the design & code for specific problems that you may face. The open source revolution brings even more access to knowledge to the learning programmer. Join or lurk about an open source project and learn from other more experienced coders. I like to visit www.codeproject.com for some reason, but there are a lot of places.<P>Mainly, find a programming language (I recommend C++) that clicks with you, and provides easy ways to program in the paradigms (procedural, object-oriented, rules-based?) you wish to use (which may be several, depending on each individual project). Get a book that you find is written in a way that is easy to read that covers the concepts of the language, and eventually get a more elaborate, reference-like book for all the low-level stuff that you may encounter.<P>"...To sum up, I recommend an approach that<BR>– proceeds from the concrete to the abstract,<BR>– presents language features in the context of the programming and design techniques that they exist<BR>to support,<BR>– presents code relying on relatively high-level libraries before going into the lower-level details (nec-essary<BR>to build those libraries),<BR>– avoids techniques that do not scale to real-world applications,<BR>– presents common and useful techniques and features before details, and<BR>– focus on concepts and techniques (rather than language features)." - Bjarne Stroustrup, from "Learning Standard C++ as a New Language", published in The C/C++ Users Journal and online at http://www.research.att.com/~bs/new_learning.pdf<P>Links:<BR>- Bjarne Stroustrup's C++ page (has many useful links and FAQ's) http://www.research.att.com/~bs/C++.html<P>- kaoruAngel</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">theNorio</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">pretty sweet copy/paste   <IMG SRC="http://www.ethernalquest.com/ubb/biggrin.gif"><BR>it's like watching a commercial,<P>I think i understood that C++ is definitely the way to go, and look for books by.. Booch.. and something about MSDN,<BR>ill be looking for books, more specifically with those author names, and ill check out the websites you mentioned<BR>-big thanks too<p>[This message has been edited by theNorio (edited 04-08-2001).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">kaoruAngel</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">C++ is definitely a good language, with a large userbase (which means easy access to help, example, libraries,...), and support for objec-oriented programming. There are many options (Java, Visual Basic, Delphi, C#, SmallTalk,...) out there, and you might nto want to stick just one, either.<P>MSDN is the Microsoft Developers Network (msdn.microsoft.com -- I think).<P>Booch has several good OO (object-oriented) books, but mine was an old one dealing with OOD/A (objext oriented design & analysis).<P>Your welcome, and good luck.<P>- kaoruAngel</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Icon</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">My brother MasTerKeyZ was teaching me C++ before he died, and I've learned a bit since then, but not much...<P>However, I'd be happy to teach you all that I know, which would cover the basics, and a BIT of more advanced stuff... the biggest thing missing from my knowledge is probably string manipulation... I can use char arrays for strings, but not manipulate them.<P>For a great C++ compiler I recommend Dev C++ Bloodshed HIGHLY, from my experience, it is way more user friendly then Microsoft or Borland... and it's completely free.<P>in fact, you can get a copy from my website at http://icon187.virtualave.net/bloodshed.zip<P>I have yet been unable to find any books or documentation that can teach me as fast and well as Mas was able to, and if anyone has some site to recommend, I'd greatly appreciate it also.<P>If you are interested in the very basics, I'd be happy to work with you, you can EMail me at Icon@icon187.virtualave.net and I will do what I can with what I know so far.<P> - Icon<BR>---------------------------<BR>- In memory of MasTerKeyZ -</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
